const faqs = [
  {
    q: "My LG refrigerator is making a clicking sound every few seconds and not cooling. What is it?",
    a: "That rhythmic click-buzz every 2-3 seconds from the back of the unit is the compressor attempting to start, failing, and resetting. The code you'll see in diagnostic mode is 67 — compressor lock. Before assuming the compressor has failed, the first thing we check is the start relay. The relay is a small plug-on component at the compressor. Remove it, shake it — if it rattles, the internal resistor has broken. A rattling relay produces identical symptoms to compressor failure and costs about $25 to replace. We've made that $25 fix on calls where the homeowner was bracing for a $600 compressor. We check the relay on every clicking LG refrigerator call before quoting anything more expensive."
  },
  {
    q: "Is my LG refrigerator compressor covered under warranty?",
    a: "Following the Rosen v. LG Electronics class action settlement, LG extended its Inverter Linear Compressor warranty to 10 years (parts and labor) for models manufactured 2014–2022. Covered series include LFXS, LFXC, LMXS, LMXC, LRMVS, LRMVC, LSXS, LSXC, LTCS, and LRTLS. If your unit falls in this range and the compressor has genuinely failed (relay is good, windings test correctly, compressor still won't run), LG covers the part and we handle the warranty claim process. You pay labor only. We check coverage on every LG compressor call before quoting anything."
  },
  {
    q: "What does the OE error code mean on my LG washer?",
    a: "OE means the drain cycle didn't complete. In the large majority of OE cases — we'd say 80% or more of what we actually see — the cause is a clogged drain pump filter. LG front-load washers have a filter behind a small access panel at the lower front of the machine. It needs cleaning quarterly. Most homeowners have never cleaned it and don't know it's there. We clean it, show you where it is, and show you how. In most OE calls, no parts are needed and the service fee covers the entire visit."
  },
  {
    q: "My LG washer shows LE. Does that mean the motor failed?",
    a: "Not necessarily. LE stands for motor error — locked motor. The most common trigger is an overloaded drum. The motor can't turn the drum against the resistance of too much laundry, triggers LE, and stops. Try running an empty cycle or a smaller load. If LE clears, you've found the cause. If LE appears consistently on normal load sizes, then the motor, hall sensor, or control board needs diagnosis. We see LE misdiagnosed as motor failure when the actual cause was just an overloaded machine — a pattern especially common in households that frequently overstuff the drum."
  },
  {
    q: "Does hard water in Southern California affect LG refrigerators?",
    a: "Yes, in specific ways. SoCal water — especially in the San Fernando Valley (LADWP), the Conejo Valley (Cal-Am), and parts of Orange County — carries significant mineral content. LG refrigerators with water dispensers and ice makers accumulate scale on the inlet valve screen over time. When scale restricts the valve, ice production slows — hollow cubes, reduced output, eventually none. We inspect and clean the inlet screen on every LG refrigerator water system call, and we recommend a water filter upstream of the refrigerator supply line for high-hardness areas. A $40 inline filter prevents what would otherwise become a $180-250 valve replacement."
  },
  {
    q: "How much does LG appliance repair cost in Southern California?",
    a: "Our diagnostic fee is $89, credited toward the repair. OE filter cleaning is typically a service-call-only charge. Start relay replacement runs $89 (service) + $25 (part). Door latch replacement $120-180. Heating element $150-230. Ice maker assembly $180-280. Compressor replacement: under warranty, you pay labor only ($200-350). Out of warranty, $400-600 in parts plus labor. We give a written estimate before starting any work."
  },
  {
    q: "What is the d80, d90, or d95 code on my LG dryer?",
    a: "These are vent blockage warnings — the dryer's airflow sensor is detecting 80%, 90%, or 95% restriction in the exhaust vent. This is not a component failure — the vent run needs cleaning. We clear the vent on every LG dryer call in Southern California and check the exterior cap for blockage. If the warning persists after vent cleaning, the moisture sensor bar or control board may need attention — but vent blockage is the cause in the overwhelming majority of these calls."
  }
];

