  <section class="brand-intro">
    <div class="brand-intro-inner">
      <h2>What We've Learned From Thousands of LG Calls in Southern California</h2>
      <p>LG has been one of the most popular appliance brands in SoCal for over a decade. Their French door refrigerators, front-load washers, and ranges are in homes from Sherman Oaks to Newport Beach to Thousand Oaks. We handle LG calls daily across all three counties and the failure patterns are well-mapped by now.</p>
      <p>The most important thing we've learned: the most expensive-sounding LG diagnoses are often wrong. The refrigerator making a clicking sound every few seconds — it might be a $25 relay, not a $600 compressor. The washer throwing an OE drain error — it's almost certainly a clogged filter, not a failed pump. The LE motor error — try a smaller load before assuming motor failure.</p>
      <p>We don't lead with the expensive answer. We check the cheap possibilities first, explain what we find, and give you an honest recommendation. That's what we'd want if we were calling a repair company.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="brand-context">
    <div class="brand-context-inner">
      <div class="section-number">01</div>
      <div class="brand-context-content">
        <h2>The $25 Fix That Looks Like a $600 Problem</h2>
        <p>Every week we get calls across Southern California that sound the same: LG refrigerator, clicking every 2-3 seconds from the back, nothing cooling. Homeowners have Googled it, read about linear compressor failures, and are mentally preparing for a major repair or replacement.</p>
        <p>The symptom — that rhythmic click-buzz-click — is the compressor trying to start, failing, and the overload protection resetting. It does indicate something is wrong with the compressor circuit. But it doesn't tell you what.</p>
        <p>There's a component called the start relay — sometimes called the PTC relay — that plugs directly onto the compressor terminals. It provides the initial current surge needed to start the compressor motor. When the relay fails internally (the ceramic resistor breaks), it can't provide that surge. The compressor tries to start without it, fails, and the overload trips. The clicking pattern is identical to a seized or mechanically failed compressor.</p>
        <p>Checking the relay takes 60 seconds. Remove it from the compressor pins, shake it near your ear. If it rattles, the resistor has broken. Replace the relay — around $25 — and the compressor starts normally. We've made this fix on dozens of calls where the homeowner had already been quoted a compressor replacement. When the relay tests solid and the compressor winding resistance is in spec but the unit still won't start, then you're dealing with a genuine internal compressor failure. That's when warranty coverage becomes the important question.</p>

        <h2>The LG Compressor Warranty — How It Actually Works</h2>
        <p>The Rosen v. LG Electronics class action established that LG's Inverter Linear Compressor had higher-than-expected failure rates, particularly in models sold 2014-2022. As part of the settlement, LG extended the warranty to 10 years from purchase date — parts and labor — for the covered model series.</p>
        <p>When a covered unit needs a compressor, LG ships the replacement to us through their service portal. LG reimburses us for labor. The homeowner pays nothing for parts and nothing for labor beyond our service fee. For a compressor that would cost $400-600 in parts alone out of warranty, this is a significant difference.</p>
        <p>The process: we verify your model, serial number, and purchase date through LG's system. If covered, we submit the work order, order the compressor (typically 2-5 business days), perform the replacement, and file the claim. We handle all of that. The homeowner's role is to have a purchase receipt or be able to confirm the purchase date — which LG can sometimes verify through retailer records.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

